#X text 847 28 Messages sent by the midimix object begin with the letters mm \, followed by the column number \, and a letter that indicates what kind of control was moved. The letter may be "s" for slider \, "k" for knob \, or "b" for button. For knobs and buttons \, the letter is followed by a number that indicates which knob or button was moved. For example \, the message mm1s contains the value of the slider in column 1 . The message mm1k1 contains the value of knob 1 in column 1 . The message mm1b3 contains the value of button 3 in column 1 ., f 78;
#X text 848 573 Except for the MIDI device number field \, the number fields in the midimix object are output only. Typing in those fields has no effect., f 78;
#X text 36 621 The MIDI Mix controller has 9 columns of controls. The first 8 columns each have 1 slider \, 3 knobs \, 2 physical buttons \, and 1 virtual button (button 2). Button 2 is toggled by pressing the "SOLO" button with button 1 . The 9th column has 4 buttons and a slider. The "SEND ALL" and "SOLO" buttons do not send MIDI messages. SEND ALL sends the values of all controls to the midimix object. It is a good idea to press SEND ALL every time you open a patch that uses the midimix object. The midimix object treats each button as a toggle. Press once to turn it on \, press it again to turn it off. Buttons have LEDs to indcate whether they are on or off., f 78;
#X text 847 182 Buttons send a value of 0 or 1 . Knobs and sliders send a value from 0 to 127 \, so they will usually need to be scaled. In the example below \, the value from slider 1 in column 1 is divided by 127 to give a number from 0 to 1 to control the volume., f 78;
#X text 36 145 To use the MIDI Mix with Pure Data \, connect it to your computer before starting Pure Data. After starting Pure Data \, click on "MIDI settings..." in the Media menu. Add "MIDI Mix" to both the Input Devices list and the Output Devices list. It must be in the same position in both lists. If the MIDI Mix is device number 2 in the Input list \, it must also be number 2 in the Output list. Enter the MIDI device number in the white number box. Press the "SEND ALL" button on the MIDI mix. If it was correctly installed \, the number fields will be filled in from the knob and slider settings on the device., f 78;
#X text 848 631 Although you can toggle a button by clicking on it in the midimix abstraction \, it will confuse the MIDI Mix if you are using more than one midimix abstraction in your patches. It is a good idea to only have one midimix abstraction. It doesn't need to be in the same patch that receives the messages., f 78;
#X obj 1487 745 tgl 24 0 empty empty empty 0 -12 0 16 #fcfcfc #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X obj 1487 774 s tap_mm9b1;
#X text 848 750 If you want to toggle a MIDI Mix button from your code \, you can add a tap_ prefix to the button name as in this example:;
#X text 36 28 The midimix object allows Pure Data patches to receive input from the AKAI MIDI Mix. It has 59 outputs \, too many to use outlets \, so it sends a Pure Data message whenever a control is moved. It assumes that the MIDI Mix is using the factory settings. If you have changed the settings \, you must either restore the factory settings \, or edit midimix.pd before using it., f 78;
#X text 847 314 This example receives messages from controls in column 1 to control a simple ring modulator. Button 1 in column 1 turns it on or off. The slider in column 1 controls the volume. Knobs 1 and 2 control the frequencies., f 27;
